Let $\sqrt{1+4a^2}=x$ and substitute into the $\frac{7x-4a^2-1}{x+3}=2$, it's solvable now!</think> <answer>$\frac{7a\sqrt{1+4a^2}-4a^2-1}{\sqrt{1+4a^2}+3}=\frac{7a^2-1}{\sqrt{1+4a^2}+3}$,sin $\sqrt{1+4a^2}\Rightarrow 7a^2-1=2（\sqrt{1+4a^2}+3）$!\end{answer}
$$ \left\{ \begin{matrix}
& \sqrt{1+4a^2}+3\ge 0 \\ 
& 7a^2-1\ge 0 \\ 
\end{matrix} \right.\Rightarrow  a\ge \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{7}}. $$

Let $x=1+4a^2$, we have
\begin{align*}
\dfrac{7x-4a^2-1}{\sqrt{1+4a^2}+3}&=\dfrac{7x-\dfrac{x-1}{4}-1}{\sqrt{x}+3}\\
&=\dfrac{27x-5}{4\sqrt{x}+3}=\dfrac{27\sqrt{x}+27}{4\sqrt{x}+3}\\
&=\dfrac{27}{4}+\dfrac{1}{4}\cdot \dfrac{9}{\sqrt{x}+3/4}\\
&\geqslant \dfrac{27-3}{4}=\dfrac{11}{2}
\end{align*}
The equality holds and only holds for $x=9$, therefore we have 
$$\dfrac{7\sqrt{(2a)^2+(1)^2}-4a^2-1}{\sqrt{1+4a^2}+3}=2$$ if and only if $a=\dfrac{2\sqrt{2}}{3}$.
Therefore, \begin{align*}
\dfrac{7\sqrt{(2a)^2+(1)^2}-4a^2-1}{\sqrt{1+4a^2}+3}=&2\\
\iff \dfrac{7x-4a^2-1}{\sqrt{1+4a^2}+3}&=2\\
&\iff x^2+2\sqrt{3}x-5=0\\
&\iff x=\sqrt{1+4a^2}=\sqrt{7}\\
&\iff a=\dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{3}.
\end{align*}
